# Garbage Collection (GC)

Garbage Collection is the automatic process of removing objects that are **no longer reachable**.

## Example

```java
Student s = new Student();
s = null;
```

After assigning `null`, the object becomes **eligible for Garbage Collection**.

> **Note:** Eligible for GC does **not** mean it is immediately removed. The JVM decides when to perform Garbage Collection.

---

#  Types of Garbage Collection

## 1. Minor GC

- Cleans the Young Generation
- Fast and frequent

---

## 2. Major GC

- Cleans the Old Generation
- Slower than Minor GC

---

## 3. Full GC

- Cleans the entire Heap
- Most expensive GC operation

---

# ⚙️ Common Garbage Collectors

## Serial GC

- Uses a single thread
- Suitable for small applications

```text
-XX:+UseSerialGC
```

---

## Parallel GC

- Uses multiple threads
- Focuses on maximum throughput

```text
-XX:+UseParallelGC
```

---

## G1 (Garbage First) GC

- Default in modern Java versions
- Suitable for large Heap sizes
- Predictable pause times

```text
-XX:+UseG1GC
```

---

## ZGC

- Designed for very large heaps
- Extremely low pause times

```text
-XX:+UseZGC
```

---

## Shenandoah GC

- Low-pause Garbage Collector
- Developed by Red Hat

```text
-XX:+UseShenandoahGC
```

